  <prompt>
    All callers of `AnalysisOrchestrationService.ExecuteAnalysisAsync` have been migrated (Wave 9 task 091
    handled chat-summarize, Wave 4 task 041 handled the rest). This task DELETES the method itself plus
    every helper/branch/private method that becomes unreachable as a result. Per spec Q6 (RESOLVED) and
    FR-11, there is NO backward-compatibility shim. Big-bang delete. This is a pure-deletion task — no
    replacement code. The whole point of Wave 4 is to remove this dead path.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior .NET backend developer performing a precise deletion + cascading-dead-code cleanup. Goal:
    every line associated with the legacy direct-invocation path is gone. Use Roslyn / IDE "find usages"
    + grep to identify cascade. Verify build + tests after each deletion sweep.
  </role>

  <goal>
    After this task:
    1. `ExecuteAnalysisAsync` method DELETED from `AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs`
    2. Any private helper methods used ONLY by `ExecuteAnalysisAsync` DELETED (cascade cleanup)
    3. Any DTOs / response types used ONLY by `ExecuteAnalysisAsync` DELETED (if their only consumer was this method)
    4. Test fixtures referencing `ExecuteAnalysisAsync` DELETED (per task 040 audit list)
    5. DI registration for `IAnalysisOrchestrationService` re-evaluated: if the interface still has OTHER methods serving live consumers, keep it; if `ExecuteAnalysisAsync` was its only public method, DELETE the interface too
    6. `dotnet build` passes; `dotnet test` passes
    7. Post-task grep for `ExecuteAnalysisAsync` returns zero hits across `src/` + `tests/`
    8. Publish-size SHRINK documented (this is dead-code removal)
  </goal>

