  <steps>
    <step order="0" name="Rigor Declaration">
      Output: 🔒 RIGOR LEVEL: FULL · 📋 REASON: code-impl in BFF (.cs deletion, tag bff-api+code-impl+deletion, ADR-013+029+038 applicable) — quality gates Step 9.5 required · Proceeding with Step 0...
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Load context">
      Read project CLAUDE.md + spec.md FR-11 + plan.md Wave 4 + .claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md + task 040 audit doc.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Verify prerequisites">
      Confirm task 041 marked ✅ AND task 091 marked ✅ in TASK-INDEX.
      Run Grep pattern="ExecuteAnalysisAsync" glob="**/*.cs" output_mode="content" -n true. Expected: ONLY the method declaration + any test fixtures from audit. If a production caller remains, STOP and report — go back to task 041.
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Read AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs in full">
      Open the file. Identify: `ExecuteAnalysisAsync` method body, every private helper it calls (record their names), every DTO it constructs/returns (record their names).
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Delete ExecuteAnalysisAsync">
      Remove the method body, signature, and XML doc comment. Save.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Build — surface cascade">
      Run: `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/`
      Capture compiler warnings about unused private members. This is the cascade list.
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Delete cascade — first sweep">
      For each warning-flagged private member (helper method, field, constant): verify it has no other consumer; if confirmed unused, DELETE. Save.
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Build — second sweep">
      Repeat build → identify next round of newly-unused members. Delete. Continue until build is clean and no orphan-private-member warnings.
    </step>
    <step order="8" name="Re-evaluate IAnalysisOrchestrationService interface">
      Inspect the interface. If `ExecuteAnalysisAsync` was its only method, DELETE the interface, the implementation class boilerplate, and the DI registration. If other live methods remain, leave interface in place but remove the deleted method's signature.
    </step>
    <step order="9" name="Delete test fixtures">
      For each test reference identified in task 040 audit, DELETE the test method (or entire test class if all its methods reference the deleted method). Per ADR-038: do NOT keep "smoke tests" of removed functionality.
    </step>
    <step order="10" name="Build + run tests">
      Run: `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/`
      Run: `dotnet test tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/`
      Goal: 0 errors, 0 NEW warnings, all surviving tests pass.
    </step>
    <step order="11" name="Verify grep state — FR-11 acceptance gate">
      Run: Grep pattern="ExecuteAnalysisAsync" glob="**/*.cs" output_mode="files_with_matches"
      Required: ZERO hits across `src/` and `tests/`. If non-zero, find + delete remaining references before proceeding.
    </step>
    <step order="11.5" name="Quality gates (FULL rigor)">
      Run `/code-review` on the modified file(s). Run `/adr-check` against ADR-013 + ADR-029 + ADR-038 + bff-extensions.md.
      Fix any findings before commit.
    </step>
    <step order="12" name="Publish + size check (NFR-01 partial — running tally toward task 047 wave check)">
      Run: dotnet publish -c Release src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/ -o deploy/api-publish-task042/
      Measure compressed size; document delta vs prior baseline. Expected: NEGATIVE shrink (this is the largest single deletion in Wave 4).
    </step>
    <step order="13" name="Update current-task.md + TASK-INDEX">
      Mark task 042 status complete; advance current-task.md to task 043.
    </step>
    <step order="14" name="Commit">
      Commit deletion with conventional message.
      Example: refactor(bff/r7)!: DELETE AnalysisOrchestrationService.ExecuteAnalysisAsync + cascade (Wave 4 task 042, FR-11)
      Use `!` to flag breaking-change in commit per conventional-commits convention (legacy direct path removed per Q6 RESOLVED — no compatibility shim).
    </step>
  </steps>

